The language about "recent global economic and financial developments may restrain economic activity somewhat and are likely to put further downward pressure on inflation in the near term" is very distinctive — this exact phrasing was introduced at the September 2015 FOMC meeting, when global market turmoil (particularly from China) caused the Fed to delay liftoff. This language about global developments putting downward pressure on inflation was new/changed from the July 2015 statement.

The reference to "holdings of longer-term securities at sizable levels" is consistent with the post-QE3 period (late 2014 through 2015) when the Fed had stopped purchases but was maintaining its balance sheet.

