This language about "cumulative tightening of monetary policy" and "lags with which monetary policy affects economic activity and inflation" was introduced in the November 2022 FOMC statement and continued through subsequent meetings during the tightening cycle. The phrase "pace of future increases in the target range" indicates the Fed was still hiking rates (not yet paused), and the "unchanged context" note suggests this is not the meeting where this language was first introduced.

This specific forward guidance language was used from November 2022 through early 2023. The mention of "future increases" (plural, still expecting more hikes) and "unchanged" context narrows it to December 2022 or February 2023. Given the "unchanged" designation suggesting it had been used before, December 2022 or February 2023 are most likely.

